\".HEADING 2 "Aim"
\".PP
\"To investigate the total resistance of a circuit when resistors are placed in series vs. in
\"parallel.
\".HEADING 2 "Theory"
\".PP
\"Ohm's Law states that the resistance of a circuit, R, is given by the equation $R = V smallover I$,
\"where:
\".LEFT
\".IL 6n
\"V = potential difference across the resistor (V)
\"I = current through the resistor (A)
\"R = resistance of resistor to current flow ($OMEGA$)
\".IL -33p
\"
\".PP
\"For resistors in series, the total resistance of the circuit, $R sub T$, can be obtained through
\"the equation
\".EQ
\"R sub T ~~=~~ R sub 1 ~+~ R sub 2 ~+~ R sub 3 ~+~ ~...
\".EN
\".PP
\"where $R sub n$ is the resistance of the $n sup th$ resistor.
\"
\".PP
\"For resistors in parallel, the total resistance of the circuit, $R sub T$, is defined as
\".EQ
\"1 over {R sub T} ~~=~~ 1 over {R sub 1} ~+~ 1 over {R sub 2} ~+~ 1 over {R sub 3} ~+~ ~...
\".EN
\".PP
\"where $R sub n$ is the resistance of the $n sup th$ resistor.
\"
\".PP
\"Given resistors with known resistances, these equations can be used to verify Ohm's Law.
\".HEADING 2 "Diagram"
\".HEADING 2 "Method"
\".PP
\"The power supply was made sure to be off. The first circuit was put together using banana
\"connectors, with the two resistors in series. Two multimetres were used in the circuit, with one
\"connected in series measuring current and another connected in parallel measuring voltage. The
\"circuit was made sure to be correct and the power supply was switched on. The power supply voltage
\"was set to 0.5 V and measurements of current and voltage were taken for each increment of 0.5 V up
\"to 5 V. Ohm's law was then used to calculate the resistance of the circuit. The same steps were
\"repeated for the second circuit, with the resistors placed in parallel.
