\".HEADING 2 "Result"
\".PP
\"The equation of a line is defined as $y = m x + c$. Ohm's law states that $R = V smallover I$,
\"which can be rearranged as $V = R I$. This takes the form of $y = m x$ (where c is 0 because
\"current, voltage and resistance are proportional to each other). As such, a line graphed with
\"voltage (V) on the Y axis and current (I) on the X axis will have a slope equal to the resistance
\"R.
\"
\".PP
\"The resistance obtained from the line can be compared against the expected resistances obtained
\"through the equations $R sub T = R sub 1 + R sub 2 + R sub 3 + ...$ for resistors in series, and
\"$1 smallover {R sub T} = 1 smallover {R sub 1} + 1 smallover {R sub 2}$ for resistors in parallel.
\"
\".PP
\"Using a 300 $OMEGA$ and a 220
\"$OMEGA$ resistor gave expected resistances of:
\".EQ C
\"300 ~+~ 220 ~~=~~ 520~mark OMEGA roman{"  for the series circuit"}
\".EN
\".sp -0.2i
\".EQ
\"1 ~~/~~ {( 1 smallover 300 ~~+~~ 1 smallover 220 )} ~~=~~ 126.92~lineup OMEGA
\"roman{"  for the parallel circuit"}
\".EN
\"The resistances measured were 520.64 $OMEGA$ and 128.33 $OMEGA$
\"respectively, giving percentage variations of 0.1% $( {520.64 - 520} smallover 520 times 100% )$
\"and 1.1% $( {128.33 - 126.92} smallover 126.92 times 100% )$. 
\".HEADING 2 "Discussion"
\".PP
\"The aim of the experiment was fully attained. The expected resistances calculated with the
\"equations $R sub T = R sub 1 + R sub 2$ and $1 smallover {R sub T} = 1 smallover {R sub 1} +
\"1 smallover {R sub 2}$ matched almost exactly the resistances calculated via Ohm's Law.
\"The graphed lines indicate a proportional relationship between voltage, current and resistance.
\"The resistances were measured to a very high degree of accuracy, and as such I can't suggest any
\"possible sources of error or improvements.
\".HEADING 2 "Conclusion"
\".PP
\"The total resistance of resistors in series is defined as $R sub T = R sub 1 + R sub 2$, and the
\"total resistance of resistors in parallel is defined as $1 smallover {R sub T} = 1 smallover
\"{R sub 1} + 1 smallover {R sub 2}$. My final results were 520.64 $OMEGA$ and 128.33 $OMEGA$, with
\"percentage variations of 0.1% and 1.1%.
